Conquest of the Empire is an asymmetric random map. Take command of a dying civilization, beset on all sides by barbarians. Though far past its prime, the remaining Imperial strength is more than a match for any single invader.Player 1 (Player 2 in Conquest of the Imperium) controls the Imperial Capital, a city whose strength is proportional to map size. The capital includes a number of advantages: free housing and research buildings, barracks, accessible relics, some fortifications, multiple town centers (for some map sizes), a few elite troops, and stone reserves. In larger maps, Imperial possessions include smaller cities with a town center and a nearby relic.To overcome this disparity, other players are expected to work together. The total number of players should not exceed the recommendation of the map size, or barbarians are likely to possess buildings in the capital. Barbarians start with a small army to harass cities and help fend off Imperial attacks. These armies have a random composition, which can be different for each barbarian tribe.In Regicide games, Barbarians get double starting troops, but no castle. The Imperial forces will have a king in each town, an extra castle, and a few hero guards in the capital.Many Imperial cities have already been overrun. Their rubble-filled remains are strewn across the map, offering various relicts of their former glory. All extra stone mines and relics will be found in ruined cities, as well as some old buildings, refugees, deserters willing to join whoever finds them, and bandits.This pack also includes Fallen Empire, where the capital is no more, and all players start as barbarians fighting among the ruins.This map was originally made for Aok: Realms mod, where it has several more feautures: http://www.moddb.com/mods/aok-realms

The Scandinavian Mountains run through the Norwegian and Swedish borders, connecting to the Finnish side at the Three-Country Cairn. Vast forests, fell, rivers (älvar), fjords, lakes, and a cold climate characterizes the landscape. The Norwegian Sea and Barents Sea encompasses the northern parts of the Cap of the North, while the Bothnian Bay lies to the south and the White Sea to the east. It is debated which of the last-mentioned waters that was referred to the mythological Gandvík, the Bay of Serpents, but it probably was the latter.

Sápmi is the land of the Sámi people, the indigenous people of the northern parts of Norway, Sweden, Finland and the Kola Peninsula (Russia), also known as Fennoscandia. To survive in the freezing and sometimes barren landscape the Sámi traditionally engage in coastal fishing, fur trapping and sheep herding. They are however best known for their reindeer herding and their semi-nomadic lifestyle. Even though findings imply that some trade between the Sámi and foreign rulers occurred during the Viking Age and the Middle ages, it is unsure how well-spread it was. The area is also inhabited by the Kven people in Kvenland, who now have migrated from northern Sweden and Finland (Lappmarken) to northern Norway (Finnmark). Specialized in hunting and farming, the Kvens also acted as middlemen in the trading activities between Sámi and others. In the early Viking Age, the kingdom of Hålogaland existed in western Norway, populated by the Hölgi. Here lies the famous archipelago of Lofoten. South of Hålogaland were the kingdom of Namdalen. Furthermore, the Vikings used the term “Bjarmaland” to describe the territory of Arkhangelsk Oblast and the Kola Peninsula. Tornedalians is also worth a mention, living at both sides of the Swedish and Finnish border.

The colonization of Sápmi began around end of the first millennium by Norwegian, Swedish and Russian tax-collectors (later called birkarls in Sweden). Christian missions hurried up the process. Also, from the 18th and 19th centuries the Swedish and Norwegian governments started a forced assimilation upon the Sámi.

Sicily is the largest island in the Mediterranean Sea.

The earliest archaeological evidence of human activity on the island dates from as early as 12,000 BC. By around 750 BC, Sicily had three Phoenician and a dozen Greek colonies and it was later the site of the Sicilian Wars and the Punic Wars. After the fall of the Roman Empire in the 5th century AD, Sicily was ruled during the Early Middle Ages by the Vandals, the Ostrogoths, the Byzantine Empire, and the Emirate of Sicily. The Norman conquest of southern Italy led to the creation of the County of Sicily in 1071, that was succeeded by Kingdom of Sicily, a state that existed from 1130 until 1816.

Sicily has a rich and unique culture, especially with regard to the arts, music, literature, cuisine, and architecture. It is also home to important archaeological and ancient sites, such as the Necropolis of Pantalica, the Valley of the Temples, Erice and Selinunte. Byzantine, Arab, Roman and Norman rule over Sicily has led to a blend of cultural influences.

En 917 el ejército búlgaro asestó una aplastante derrota sobre los bizantinos en la batalla de Aqueloo que resultó en la total supremacía militar búlgara en la península balcánica. Los bizantinos fueron derrotados nuevamente en Katasyrtai en 917 y en Pegai en 922. Los búlgaros capturaron la importante ciudad de Adrianópolis en Tracia y se apoderaron de la capital del Thema de la Hélade, Tebas, en el sur de Grecia. Después del desastre de Aqueloo la diplomacia bizantina incitó al Principado de Serbia para atacar a Bulgaria en su retaguardia hacia el oeste, pero la amenaza serbia fue contenida con facilidad. Sin embargo, en 924 los serbios lograron emboscar y derrotar a un pequeño ejército provocando una importante campaña de represalia que terminó con la anexión de Serbia a finales de ese mismo año.

Simeón era consciente de que necesitaba apoyo naval para conquistar Constantinopla y en 922 envió emisarios al califa fatimí Abdullah al-Mahdi Billah en Mahdia para negociar la ayuda de la poderosa armada árabe. El califa acordó enviar a sus propios representantes de vuelta a Bulgaria para concertar una alianza. Sin embargo, los enviados fueron capturados en el camino por los bizantinos, cerca de la costa de Calabria. El emperador Romano I Lecapeno logró disolver la alianza búlgaro-árabe con generosos regalos. Para la fecha de su muerte, el 27 de mayo de 927, Simeón I controlaba casi todas las posesiones bizantinas en los Balcanes pero no pudo apoderarse de Constantinopla.

En 927 ambos países estaban agotados por los enormes esfuerzos militares que tuvieron alto precio entre la población y la economía. El sucesor de Simeón, Pedro I, negoció un tratado de paz favorable. Los bizantinos acordaron reconocerlo como emperador de Bulgaria y de la iglesia ortodoxa búlgara como un Patriarcado independiente, así como pagar un tributo anual. La paz fue reforzada con un matrimonio entre Pedro I y la nieta de Romano I, Irene Lecapena. Este acuerdo marcó el comienzo de un período de cuarenta años de relaciones pacíficas entre las dos potencias, una época de estabilidad y prosperidad para Bulgaria y el Imperio bizantino.

Gotland is the largest island in both Sweden and the Baltic sea, famous for its stone formations called "rauks". Since the bedrock is made of limestone farming is made very difficult here. Upon these bedrock lies "alvar", land that consist of a thin layer of vegetation. Together with widespread marshes, pebble shores and coniferous forests Gotland has a unique environment and therefore plenty of nature reserves. Close to Gotland you can also find the islands Fårö, Karlsö Islands, Gotska Sandön and Östergarnsholm. The norsemen that inhabited Gotland was known as gutes and probably related to the goths. Still the Swedish dialect of Gotland is very distinctive, especially concerning diphthongs. During the middle ages the city of Visby, known for its city walls, became a part of the Hanseatic League and so a major trading post for seafaring merchants called "farmän". Later the Danish conquered Gotland, and in the 1400th century Visby turned into the headquarters of the Victual Brothers, pirates of the Balitic sea. The Teutonic Order then capured the island, and not until the Second Treaty of Brömsebro in 1645 Gotland became a part of Sweden once again. Though Danish soldiers destroyed the fortress Visborg when leaving Visby after a short Danish recapture. Today Visby annually holds a week-long festival celebrating its medieval history. Notable viking settlements are Västergarn and Paviken.

Southwest of Gotland lies Öland, Sweden's second largest island, with a landscape reminiscent of that of Gotland, though with much more alvar. Here towns have different dialects depending on which town on the Swedish mainland it traded with. Notable is also the ruins of Borgholm Castle and Eketorp, and the town Köpingsvik. To the west lies the Swedish mainland with cities as Norrköping, Söderköping, Västervik and Oskarshamn.

Värend was a folkland and one of the "small lands", historic territories, that was constituents of the province Småland (Smolandia), southern Sweden, and its people was called "virdar". This is the highlands of Småland, with deep forests and plenty of lakes and small rivers and creeks connecting them. The land is famous for its soil rich of stones, which made it hard to farm. As the farmers cleansed the soil they used the stones to build small stone walls and to divide the farm lands. Cists and cairns also characterize the area. At the most notable lake Helgasjön's southern shores lies the residenz city of Växjö, which has been a centre of commerce since the early middle ages. When Gustav Vasa was crowned king of Sweden a peasant uprising called the Dacke war took place here, which resulted in the death of the revolter Nils Dacke. Before the Treaty of Roskilde in 1658 Värend acted as the frontier against Denmark, which was good for trade but also resulted in many pillagings on the Swedish border.

When the vikings arrived to Iceland a quarter of the land was covered with forests. However, within a century 90% was chopped down as the people needed supplies for boats and buildings, and also because the sheep fed on the sprouts. Since the people fled from the Norwegian king it was decided that no king shall rule over Iceland. Instead, political decisions and disputes was made and solved at a "thing", a sort of folkmoot. It was later here that Leif Eriksson and his sister Freydis, children of Erik the Red, were born and embarked on a journey to Greenland and Vinland as presumably the first Europeans to ever venture there.

This is my attempt at creating a semi-realistic random map script for Western Europe. I designed it with ludicrous size in mind, and the scale is meant to be approximately on the scale of France or Germany. THIS IS NOT BALANCED! It’s not meant to be. Rather, it’s like placing your civ in the land that doesn’t care whether they are there or not. You are not guaranteed a good starting position or the same nearby resources as anybody else. This is a test of your ability to adaptat. Main features: -Woodland covers about 15% to 60% of the land, as in medieval Europe. -Mountains cover about 0% to 40% of the land, as in Europe. -Gold is extremely rare, but can sometimes be found in mountains. -Stone is somewhat rare, but can be found in rocky areas. -Fish occur in larger clumps spaced apart more than usual. -Only fish actually found in Europe and in the correct water depths can be found. -Animals generally spawn in the types of areas they would in real life (bears near woods, horses away from woods), and only the types of animals found in Europe are present. -Forests tend to be found in larger clumps. Recommendations: -Play with friends/allied AI! There is little to no gold to be found, so trading is key! -if you play on ludicrous, focus on making scouts early, most things in the map spawn in clumps so key points are more important, and you want to find them first. -Play on Nomad; you'll be able to choose a better starting location. I hope you enjoy, and please let me know if I can somehow improve this to make it more realistic or true to the idea of creating a random map script for Western Europe on the scale of a country. Special thanks to TheMadCADer and Zetnus from the random map scripting discord, without whom this wouldn't have been possible.

- Trees are concentrated according to their real-world timber concentrations. Dire Straits is an open land map with some water (mostly shallows). The resources on land are pretty normal and symmetrical for all players, but the truly randomized map generation should provide a wide variety of experiences that encourage scouting and adapting. It’s designed to be fair, but not completely predictable.

It requires the following settings:

  • 1v1 on Tiny (2-Player)
  • 2v2 on Medium (4-Player)
  • 3v3 on Normal (6-Player)
  • 4v4 on Large (8-Player)

Key features include:

  • Varied maps and player positions. Exploration is key, as players aren't always placed in a circle.
  • Only one fast fish and some shore fish per lake. Fishing doesn't overpower all other strategies.
  • Primarily land-based gameplay. Warships can be used tactically instead of just for fire galley rushes.
  • 150 wood trees. Fewer trees keeps the land more open for offensive options.

A more detailed description (with more images) is available here.

Dire Straits is built using a different process than a typical AoE2 map in order to generate unpredictable geography while validating each map with a computer program to keep things fair for both teams. For more information about how to create maps like this, including the source code for all the programs used, see this guide.

A valley filled with gold separates the teams. Any buildings constructed on the valley floor will receive additional damage. Designed for 2 equal teams.

Designed for 3v3/4v4, where teams will be placed in a convex arrangement with the 'pockets' forward and piles (or pilas?!) of gold to either side.

Gold rush, but the gold is moved to a hill in the corner far from the teams. Players/teams that put too much focus on securing the gold risk leaving themselves undefended at home.

Players only have a minimal amount of gold and stone close to their bases - the rest is collected in various key locations across the map. Players will have to reach out to secure control of these locations.

My version of the map updated for DE with improved consistency of player start locations, more extra resources distributed across the map, and use of DE terrains.

每個國家擁有一位領導人，善待他們，否則必遭天譴。

The animal emblem of the country would probably be the tribe name of the player.

為了增加遊戲刺激度，各國國名已全被惡搞，因此玩家必須藉由隊伍名稱與文明判斷其所選擇的國家。

各國整體GDP與各國人均GDP將會反映在玩家的黃金數量上。

Every country has 10 hand cannoneers, 5 elite organ guns (except civilization Portuguese), 3 bombard cannons, 3 elite conquistadors, 2 elite war wagons, 2 missionaries, and 10 other troops (except the U. S.), But the U. S. and Russia would have more troops than other countries do.

因為現實世界只有美國與俄國擁有巡洋艦，所以遊戲中，美國與俄國會有精銳維京大戰船若干艘。

The turtle ships a player owns depends on operating aircraft carriers owned by the country which the player chooses.

各國航空母艦數量將反映在玩家的龜甲船數量上。

因應現代化，當玩家可以研發槍炮的時候，很多冷兵器部隊將無法生產。

There are also many different types of water distributions that can occur, including lakes, ponds, and rivers. Keep an eye out for other additional surprises - you are not always the only inhabitant of the forest!The key to winning is to control any routes you create through the forest, mass your units before rushing, and capture any bodies of water you come across. But be wary at all times - attacks can come from any direction in The Lost Forest!To play this map:1. Open the Single Player or Multi Player game lobby2. Change Game to Random Map3. Overview:Fortress River is a Fortress-style no rush random map. Players start with walls, gates, and towers to protect their starting area. However, aside from a few forage bushes, all the resources a player needs will be outside the safety of their fortress. Thick forest hampers direct travel, and the only way to access your enemies is across a large river with broad patches of shallows which are challenging to defend. WIll you cross the river and expand your dominion? Or will the trees swallow your civilisation whole?Key random factors:-River position and orientation will vary-Shallows may vary in position and number-Team land areas may become large islands-There may be extra sheep or relics-Dogs can flyStrategy:-Use warships and transports effectively-Explore carefully, and be sure to keep an eye on your immediate area - enemies can sneak up on you through narrow paths in the forests-Defend the shallows-Cavalry excel here with their speed and armourIf you wish to develop your own random map scripts, there are links and comments inside the .RMS file.About Random Maps:Random Maps are different every time you play them; the script defines rules about the environment and units etc, and the game engine randomises the placement of terrain and units based upon these rules. The goal of HyperRandom is to provide a lot of variation, while still making it reasonably fair, by providing the same variation for every player. HyperRandom will generate maps that seem similar to standard maps, but does so totally at random.

The simplest comparison would be to compare it with MegaRandom, but on a technical level it works more like ES@The_Unknown by randomizing parameters rather than drawing from a large pool of predefined layouts.

 

I included several "switches" that can be used to turn on or off various types of generations and randomizations.  For example, making a land-only version of HyperRandom is very simple to do by just editing a few lines at the beginning.  I currently maintain two versions:

The normal version, which has most features enabled, but can generate unbalanced layouts - for example lakes in some corners but not others.  The normal version also has random starting units/buildings and also random amounts of resources per animal/bush/mine.  Note here that it gives the same random amount of each player.  


The lite version, which has the many features disabled and should essentially play out like a standard map, except that the layout is generated at random.  ie. it will have standard resources, standard starting units, no unbalanced lakes, etc.

 

This map script should run on all versions of the game and supports all lobby settings and game modes, including Empire Wars and Battle Royale.

 

To play, look for ZN@HyperRandom and ZN@HyperRandomLite in your custom map styles.
